snippet.textDisplay: I met dP Art Drawing about 4 years ago in an art club, really nice guy and very hard working. While we were struggling to make measurement to make sure the drawing look like the picture, DP just need to look at the picture and draw it, like out of nowhere POP here's the drawing and it looks exactly the same! He must have practiced a lot to get that skill, and his ability has improved a lot to get such crazy awesome videos. It's really interesting to see him and Jazza have a little fun exchange, both are very talented artists.

snippet.textDisplay: when i was bored years ago, i taught myself how to draw like this. copy photos on a paper using a pencil. i did marilyn monroe, michael jackson, james dean and and a few more. tho it was cool to see how realistic the final outcome was and how it looks so similar to the original photo, it kind of got tired of it cuz i honestly feel like i might as well just print it LOL or have it photocopied... haha like i was putting in so much effort copying the highlights and shadows of an image and yet it wasnt satisfying me anymore after the 4th or 5th drawing... i wouldnt say its cheating but to me, it just felt like i was copying an image the hard way... lol (just my opinion)
snippet.textOriginal: when i was bored years ago, i taught myself how to draw like this. copy photos on a paper using a pencil. i did marilyn monroe, michael jackson, james dean and and a few more. tho it was cool to see how realistic the final outcome was and how it looks so similar to the original photo, it kind of got tired of it cuz i honestly feel like i might as well just print it LOL or have it photocopied... haha like i was putting in so much effort copying the highlights and shadows of an image and yet it wasnt satisfying me anymore after the 4th or 5th drawing... i wouldnt say its cheating but to me, it just felt like i was copying an image the hard way... lol (just my opinion)

snippet.textDisplay:
Before you revealed your method of "cheating", I surmised that it might have been a trick of shutter speed and frame rate being different between the camera and an overhead digital projector.
Essentially, for a fraction of a second, the image is projected, and for a fraction of a second, the video camera captures a frame.
As long as those two events weren't perfectly timed together, you could record video that never sees the flickering projected image.



Similar to your method, you would still be tracing an image, but it would occur on the paper itself, and not on a computer monitor.


It's important to note that my version could be viewed from multiple camera angles, so long as the shutter of the cameras were all out of sync from the projected image.


This is the method that I think DP Art is using, because if you were truly using talent alone, you would not need to secure the paper with tape when drawing.
The only real need to secure the paper would be to keep it lined up with the projected image.
He also never shows the ceiling of the room, because you'd see the projector mounted there.


If he produces another video to rebut my claims it must be long-exposure video frames (something like 15fps so you would see the projected image) or do it outside on a sunny day sitting in a park. (Or recorded with a 360° camera so we can see the entire room.)


Stay skeptical, my friends!
